{4.4 Same colored bishop ending general case Basically the attacker has two
different strategies how to handle the pawns. They can be put on the same
color of the bishops to restrict the defending bishop or they can be put on
the other color to control more squares, attack the defending pawns and invade
with the king through the holes. The second strategy is also called
Capablanca's rule and we start with it.  A) Capablanca's rule Two pawn
weaknesses can already be fatal, if the attacking king can reach both and no
counterplay is possible:[#]} 83... Bf8 $2 {This is too passive and allows
White's king to invade in the long run on the long way via the queenside.} ({
After} 83... Kf7 {Black is quick enough to set up a drawing formation, e.g.}
84. Kc4 (84. Ke4 g6 85. Be3 Bf8 86. Bf4 Kf6 $11) 84... g6 85. Kb5 gxh5 86. gxh5
Bg5 87. Kc6 Ke7 {[#]Now Black's counterplay is always just in time, e.g.} 88.
Bc3 Bh4 89. Bd2 Bg5 90. Bb4 Bf4 91. Ba3 Kf6 92. Bxd6 Bd2 93. Bc7 Bb4 94. Bb6
Kg5 95. Bc5 Bd2 96. d6 Kxh5 97. d7 Bg5 98. Kc7 Kg6 99. Kc8 h5 100. Bb6 h4 101.
Bd8 Bxd8 102. Kxd8 h3 $11) 84. Kc4 Kd7 (84... Kf7 85. Kb5 g6 {does not help
due to} 86. Kc6 gxh5 87. gxh5 Ke7 88. Bb2 Kf7 89. Ba3 Kf6 90. Bxd6 Bg7 91. Bc5
Kf5 92. d6 Kg4 93. d7 Bf6 94. Kc7 Kxh5 95. Kc8 Kg4 96. Bb6 h5 97. Bd8 Bc3 98.
Be7 Ba5 99. Bd6 $18) 85. Kb5 Kc7 86. Ka6 Kc8 87. Kb6 Kd7 88. Kb7 Ke8 ({After} 
88... Be7 89. Bxg7 Bg5 90. Bc3 Be3 {[#]White's king returns to the kingside in
glory:} 91. Ka6 Bg5 92. Kb5 Ke7 93. Kc4 Kf7 (93... Bf6 94. Bxf6+ Kxf6 95. Kb5
$18) 94. Kd3 Bf4 95. Ke4 Bg5 96. Bd4 Be7 97. Be3 Bf8 98. Kf5 Bg7 99. Bd2 Bf8
100. Bf4 $18) 89. Kc6 Kf7 (89... Kd8 90. Bb2 Ke7 91. Ba3 Kf6 92. Bxd6 $18) 90.
Kd7 g6 (90... Be7 91. Bxg7 Bg5 92. Bb2 Bf4 93. Ba3 Kf6 94. Bxd6 $18) 91. hxg6+
Kxg6 92. Ke8 Bg7 93. Bxg7 Kxg7 94. Ke7 Kg6 95. Kxd6 Kg5 96. Ke5 Kxg4 97. d6 h5
98. d7 h4 99. d8=Q h3 100. Qd1+ Kg3 101. Qh1 1-0

